Defendant Rondell Vermont Black in court with attorney Calvin R Malone.  Defendant Rondell Vermont Black in custody.  Megan P Carmody appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  

Sentencing proceeded.  PSI Report reviewed; corrections set forth on the record.  Statements made by State, defense, and defendant. 
 
The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 8 YEARS, CONSECUTIVE to any other time being served with credit for 140 days served. The INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 4 YEARS.  The MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION IS 4 YEARS.

The defendant IS NOT eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program.  The defendant IS eligible for the Substance Abuse Program AFTER SERVING 2 1/2 YEARS OF THIS SENTENCE.

CONDITIONS OF SUPERVISION:
*Obtain Mental health assessment- successfully complete follow-up treatment- take prescribed meds in the manner as prescribed by a treating  physician only;
*Obtain AODA assessment and successfully complete follow-up treatment;
*Absolute sobriety (no alcohol/no illegal drugs) with random urine screens and breathalyzer tests;
*No drug dealing or association with drug community (drug users/dealers or drug houses);
*Cooperate with any and all rules set forth by the probation agent;
*No new law violations rising to the level of probable cause;
*No contact with any Tri City National Bank;
*Obtain/maintain full time employment;
*Participate in Cognitive Thinking program;
*Obtain GED or HSED;
*Pay all supervision fees;
*Provide DNA sample- pay surcharge;
*Pay mandatory surcharge, fees, assessments, surcharges,and all other mandatory costs; 

State in compliance with victim rights legislation.  The Court ordered restitution in the stipulated amount of $1950.00 payable to Tri City National Bank- to be paid first.  The Court ordered that all financial obligations and restitution be paid through collection of sums by the Department of Corrections from 25% of funds under Sec. 973.05(4)(b) and as a condition of extended supervision.  Any amount remaining due and owing is subject to civil judgment.  Pursuant to Wisconsin Statutes Section 973.176, the Court advised the defendant of the following restrictions:  Firearm possession and Voting.  Appeal rights given by the court.
Filed;
